File: A Curro classroom. Supplied JOHANNESBURG - Private education group Curro has reported a double-digit swing back into profit. This is as schools return to normal operations and continue to weather the impact of the Covid-19 pandemic. For the year ended December 2021, the group's revenue increased by 15 percent, making a profit of R251-million, improving from a loss of R43-million in 2021. Curro says its enrolments increased by 6 percent in 2022, reversing a decline at the peak of the pandemic. Despite the impact of Covid-19 and the sluggish economy, Curro says its results reflect the company's resilient business model, underpinned by its robust offering.